[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Most Common Mistakes in Chess"]
[ChapterName "Mistake 7: Grabbing too much material at a risk"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/xx2nOKJv/V54wei5w"]
[FEN "8/4r1bk/p2Q2bp/1p2p1q1/5p2/2P5/PP2BPPP/R4RK1 w - - 2 24"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.07.21"]
[UTCTime "03:10:33"]

{ White is already up an exchange (rook for bishop) and a pawn. Extra material gain is less important from here. }
24. Qxa6? { Too greedy to gain more material. } (24. f3! { Stopping any of Black's kingside attacks first! } 24... e4 25. fxe4 Bxe4 26. Bf3 { White will now easily convert the win with the existing material advantage. }) 24... e4 25. Qxb5? { Greed will be punished } 25... Re5! { Black now seizes the initiative, and f3 is coming up next. } 26. Qc6 f3 { White is now forced the give up the bishop to stop mate. } *


[Event "🔥🔥: Mistake 8: Not having a long term plan"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/fNOVLINj/5hkMCEoi"]
[Date "2020.07.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Most Common Mistakes in Chess"]
[ChapterName "Mistake 8: Not having a long term plan"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/xx2nOKJv/H3gZAuDE"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1n1pbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/1P2P3/2N2N2/P3BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.07.21"]
[UTCTime "03:10:33"]

10... Qc7 { The game started out as a standard King's Indian Defense. Normally, white should aim to expand on the queenside and black on the kingside. Now is the perfect time to think of what the long term plan is. Black has a backwards d6 pawn, so trying to pile up on that would be nice. } 11. Bb2? { Such a normal developing move to defend the knight, but this is inconsistent with any long term plan, most definitely not contributing to the attack on d6. The bishop should be placed on a3 at some point, not on b2. } (11. Nb5! { With the d6 pawn in mind as a target! } 11... Qb8 (11... Qb6? 12. Be3) 12. Nd2 a6 13. Nc3 Kh8 14. a4 Kg8 15. Nc4 { White will eventually continue piling up forces on the queenside with Ba3 + Qb3. Notice how all of the pieces are working together towards the common goal of the d6 pawn weakness. The benefits of long term planning }) 11... Nh5 12. Rc1 Nf4 13. Nb5 { Hitting the queen, but the knight is not on an outpost, so the strong square is only temporary. Once black successfully kicks the knight back with a6, White will be forced to retreat } 13... Qb6 14. Bc4? { Unaware of what's coming up next.. } 14... a6 { Now after knight retreats, the b4 pawn falls and White has little to no play on the queenside. Black, meanwhile, has a nice knight on f4 and is up a clean pawn } *


[Event "🔥🔥: Mistake 9: Trading bishop for knight incorrectly"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/fNOVLINj/TWNOW4ge"]
[Date "2020.07.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
